<ce:sections>
<ce:section view="all">
<ce:label>1</ce:label>
<ce:section-title>Introduction</ce:section-title>
<ce:para view="all">In recent papers by Cieslak and Dubiel <ce:cross-refs refid="bib1 bib2">[1,2]</ce:cross-refs>, the effect of alloying α-Fe with Ti was investigated by means of Mössbauer spectroscopy and TEM imaging on samples prepared by arc melting. Among the results, it was found that a purely random distribution of Ti atoms could not explain the Mössbauer spectra, and this has been attributed to the low solubility of Ti in α-Fe leading to precipitation of Ti into Fe–Ti phases and clustering of Ti, i.e. a non-random distribution within α-Fe <ce:cross-refs refid="bib1 bib2">[1,2]</ce:cross-refs>. This raises the question whether samples prepared by arc melting are suitable for studies of random impurity distributions in α-Fe. We have conducted a similar study on samples prepared by pulsed laser deposition (PLD) at room temperature. Lower sample preparation temperature compared to melting techniques results in lower mobility of atoms during preparation, and phases that may be thermodynamically unstable can be produced in this way.</ce:para>
</ce:section>
<ce:section view="all">
<ce:label>2</ce:label>
<ce:section-title>Samples and experimental details</ce:section-title>
<ce:para view="all">The samples were produced by co-deposition using PLD techniques in a UHV chamber at a base pressure of 10<ce:sup loc="post">−7</ce:sup>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>Pa. A YAG:Nd laser (<ce:italic>λ</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>=<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>1.064<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>μm) operating in the Q-switched regime at an energy of <ce:italic>E</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>=<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>150<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>mJ and with a repetition rate of 25<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>Hz was used to sequentially deposit the components from elemental <ce:sup loc="pre">57</ce:sup>Fe and Ti targets in submonolayer portions on a substrate held at room temperature. The deposition rates were calibrated in situ with a quartz microbalance and the actual overall composition of the grown Fe–Ti layers was measured by Rutherford backscattering spectrometry with 2<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>MeV He<ce:sup loc="post">2+</ce:sup> beam. By varying the deposition program, i.e. the number of laser pulses and the output energy on each target, the composition of the growing deposits could be precisely controlled. Al<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>O<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> slabs were used as substrates for the growth of approximately 1000<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>Å layers. A pure α-Fe layer was grown under the same conditions as a reference.</ce:para>
<ce:para view="all">The samples were measured by conversion electron Mössbauer spectroscopy (CEMS) with the sample mounted as a cathode in a parallel plate avalanche detector <ce:cross-ref refid="bib3">[3]</ce:cross-ref> using 25<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>mCi source of <ce:sup loc="pre">57</ce:sup>Co in Rhodium matrix. Velocities and isomer shifts are given relative to the centre of the spectrum of <ce:italic>α</ce:italic>-Fe at room temperature.</ce:para>
</ce:section>
<ce:section view="all">
<ce:label>3</ce:label>
<ce:section-title>Results and discussion</ce:section-title>
<ce:para view="all">
<ce:cross-ref refid="fig1">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
<ce:float-anchor refid="fig1"></ce:float-anchor> shows the Mössbauer spectra obtained in this study. The spectra have been analysed simultaneously in terms of two components, an alloy model and a broadened quadrupole split component. The latter component (isomer shift, <ce:italic>δ</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>∼<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>−0.11(2) mm/s and quadrupole splitting, Δ<ce:italic>E</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">Q</ce:inf>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>&lt;<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>0.6<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>mm/s) is only present in significant amount in the spectra of the highest Ti concentration (∼15% of the spectral area), and the rather broad linewidth suggests surroundings that are amorphous or of poor crystallinity. This component will be ignored as its presence does not affect the conclusions that may be drawn for the magnetically-split components from this work.</ce:para>
<ce:para view="all">The lineshape of the alloy component is in terms of a modified Wertheim model <ce:cross-ref refid="bib4">[4]</ce:cross-ref>. In this model, it is assumed that the quadrupole splitting is zero, and that changes in the magnetic hyperfine field (<ce:italic>B</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">hf</ce:inf>) and the isomer shift (<ce:italic>δ</ce:italic>) can be attributed to <ce:italic>n</ce:italic>Ti nearest neighbours (NN), <ce:italic>m</ce:italic>Ti next nearest neighbours (NNN). The numbers <ce:italic>n</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>m</ce:italic>, which depend on the concentration of Ti atoms (<ce:italic>c</ce:italic>) are derived from a binomial distribution. Accordingly, we write <ce:italic>B</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">hf</ce:inf>(<ce:italic>n</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>m</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>c</ce:italic>)<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>=<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>
<ce:italic>B</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">hf,0</ce:inf>(1<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>+<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>
<ce:italic>an</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>+<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>
<ce:italic>bm</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>+<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>
<ce:italic>kc</ce:italic>) and <ce:italic>δ</ce:italic>(<ce:italic>n</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>m</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>c</ce:italic>)<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>=<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>
<ce:italic>nδ</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">NN</ce:inf>
