</ce:display>where <ce:italic>L</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">6</ce:inf> is a Lorentzian sextet, <ce:italic>Γ</ce:italic> the linewidth and <ce:italic>P</ce:italic>(<ce:italic>n</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>m</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>c</ce:italic>) is the probability of an Fe site with <ce:italic>n</ce:italic> NN Ti atoms and <ce:italic>m</ce:italic> NNN Ti atoms in a alloy of concentration <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> in random distribution. In the analysis, there was not found any indication that these assumptions were not fulfilled. The results are gathered in <ce:cross-ref refid="tbl1">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
<ce:float-anchor refid="tbl1"></ce:float-anchor>.</ce:para>
<ce:para view="all">Despite the possibility of correlated variables, we find good determination of most variables, the dependence of isomer shift on next nearest Ti neighbour could not be determined. Cieslak and Dubiel <ce:cross-ref refid="bib1">[1]</ce:cross-ref> found the hyperfine field <ce:italic>B</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">hf</ce:inf>(0, 0, <ce:italic>c</ce:italic>) to increase slightly with concentration, but the opposite behaviour is found in our case. Apart from that, we obtain generally higher numerical values of the parameters. This last finding may suggest that the Ti concentration in the samples of Cieslak and Dubiel <ce:cross-ref refid="bib1">[1]</ce:cross-ref> was indeed lower than estimated from stoichiometry analysis. This could be attributed to the low solubility of Ti atoms in α-Fe, and is supported by the fact that they did not find the Ti atoms to be randomly distributed and direct evidence for precipitation <ce:cross-ref refid="bib2">[2]</ce:cross-ref>. One way to take a critical look at this is to look at the average magnetic field as a function of concentration as this parameter should be model independent, and not be affected by the different analysis procedures. The comparison is shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig2">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
<ce:float-anchor refid="fig2"></ce:float-anchor>.</ce:para>
<ce:para view="all">Clearly, the average magnetic hyperfine field in our case drops more rapidly compared with the behaviour from <ce:cross-ref refid="bib1">[1]</ce:cross-ref>, and follows closely a simple dilution behaviour, strengthening the interpretation that the average Ti concentration in α-Fe is lower in samples prepared by arc melting than in our case.</ce:para>
<ce:para view="all">The change of spin or charge density per one solute atom per unit cell, er <ce:italic>η</ce:italic> can now be estimated following the procedures given in, e.g. <ce:cross-ref refid="bib5">[5]</ce:cross-ref>. We find a value of <ce:italic>η</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>=<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>0.075(10), which is considerably closer to the value suggested by the Miedema and der Woude model <ce:cross-refs refid="bib6 bib7">[6,7]</ce:cross-refs> (<ce:italic>η</ce:italic>
<ce:inf loc="post">M</ce:inf>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>∼<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>0.15, see, e.g. discussion in <ce:cross-ref refid="bib1">[1]</ce:cross-ref>) than the value obtained by Cieslak and Dubiel (<ce:italic>η</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>=<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>0.035) <ce:cross-ref refid="bib1">[1]</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
</ce:section>
<ce:section view="all">
<ce:label>4</ce:label>
<ce:section-title>Conclusions</ce:section-title>
<ce:para view="all">We have investigated alloys of α-Fe<ce:inf loc="post">1−<ce:italic>x</ce:italic>
</ce:inf>Ti<ce:inf loc="post">
<ce:italic>x</ce:italic>
</ce:inf>, 0<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>&lt;<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>
<ce:italic>x</ce:italic>
<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>&lt;<ce:hsp sp="0.25"></ce:hsp>0.19 produced with pulsed laser deposition at room temperature with conversion electron Mössbauer spectroscopy. The Mössbauer spectra suggest that samples produced in this way can be regarded as purely random alloys, ideal for the study of impurity atoms in metals. Comparison with similar studies suggests that samples produced with arc melting are unreliable due to the low solubility of Ti in α-Fe. A new value of the change of spin or charge density per one solute atom per unit cell <ce:italic>η</ce:italic> is found that is closer to model predictions but deviates by factor two.</ce:para>
</ce:section>
